##With more than 100,000 people infected worldwide, why did World Health Organization wait so long to declare a new "pandemic" 

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

An expert from the World Health Organization Group believes that the term "panic" is contained in the term "pandemic" , and that the possibility of a new crown epidemic becoming a "pandemic" is of course a concern, as it has a higher fatality rate than influenza, "But we hope to delay the announcement as long as possible until we have the vaccine, which is probably another 12-18 months. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Workers prepare to disinfect a traffic hub in Dongdaegu Station, Taegu, South Korea, on February 29,2020. Figure / Fachen

By Cai Tingyi

Editor | Hao Zhou

The COVID-19 epidemic has entered the pandemic, German Health Minister Jens Spahn said on March 4, and it has not yet reached its peak. But that judgment is not yet the official word of the WHO, and when World Health Organization will announce that there is controversy and pressure.

He added that he wanted the public to get three important messages: 1) control is more important than economic interest; and 2) No one knows when the epidemic will peak, but it's important to be prepared for an early warning; 3. Stay calm during an outbreak, and trust each other even under pressure.

By the afternoon of March 6, Geneva time, 534 cases had been reported in Germany, 272 more in a single day, according to World Health Organization. In the hard hit state of North Rhine-westphalia, the outbreak began when an infected couple took part in a carnival.

Spahn's reference to a global pandemic stands in stark contrast to World Health Organization's cautious avoidance of the word "pandemic" , it also raises the debate about whether the new coronavirus constitutes a "pandemic" globally.

The World Health Organization (WHO) for the first time on February 28th raised "global risk" and "regional risk" from "high" to "very high" at the same time. On that day, five new cases were found in countries around the world, including the Netherlands, Belarus, Lithuania, New Zealand and Nigeria, the world outside of China infected with 51 countries. Since then, the global epidemic has been on the rise. As of March 6, there were 98,192 cases of global infection in 89 countries or regions, of which 80,711 were reported in China, 6,284 in South Korea, 3,858 in Italy and 3,513 in Iran, new cases are growing rapidly in Germany, France, Spain and the United Kingdom, and the United States is just beginning a large-scale national testing program. As of 9:00 a.m. Beijing Time on March 7, more than 100,000 cases had been reported worldwide.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Public Health experts disagree with World Health Organization about the definition of a pandemic and its consequences, which has led to a stalemate over whether World Health Organization should declare one.

Many public health experts consider the current situation a "pandemic" . "I think it's reasonable to call it a pandemic, " Neil Ferguson, an epidemiologist at Imperial College London, told the press. Lawlor, a medical expert at the University of Nebraska, went so far as to point out that a "pandemic" is a global spread of the virus. "We are now in a pandemic, and we are not declaring it for political reasons. "

Who director-general Tan Desai said at a press conference on March 2 that, "Does this virus have pandemic potential? Of course it is. Are we already facing this situation? Based on our assessment, no. "We have not seen an uncontrolled global spread, and we have not yet seen massive, severe symptoms or deaths.

WHO spokesman World Health Organization explained to the media that the organization has no longer used the "pandemic" as the highest level of the six-phase pandemic alert system, the term "pandemic" may be used "informally" in the future.

He further stressed to Caijing that World Health Organization had declared the global outbreak an "international public health emergency" on January 30, the highest level of alert, since then, "we've seen cases in several countries... most of these cases are traceable, which means widespread community transmission is not apparent. Some countries have even slowed or stopped transmission. "

China's approach to fighting the epidemic can be replicated, but it takes speed, money, imagination and political courage, World Health Organization's team leader, Bruce Aylward, told reporters after a recent visit to China, it is still possible for countries that act quickly to contain the outbreak.

The definition of a global pandemic

Who originally divided the epidemic situation of infectious diseases into six phases, namely: The emergence of new animal viruses in Phase 1; the infection of humans with new viruses in Phase 2; the initiation of small-scale transmission in Phase 3; and the introduction of human-to-human transmission in Phase 4; In Phase 5, community-based infections occur in two or more regions; in phase 6, community-based infections spread further across more regions and become "pandemic" globally.

Elsewhere on its website, World Health Organization defines a "pandemic" as "the spread of a new infectious virus around the world to which most people are not immune, having previously been caused mostly by zoonotic viruses. "

"It's all about geography, " says Lauren Sauer, a Johns Hopkins University Public Health expert, "It's not about the 'severity' of [ the virus ] , it's not about the number of cases, it's about whether we see [ the virus ] spread across the earth. "

Based on this criteria, the World Health Organization group classified the spread of the A / H1N1 influenza virus as a pandemic in 2009, only to find that the H1N1 pandemic did not turn out to be as severe as initially expected, a number of experts, member states and drug companies have criticized World Health Organization's Organization for being too hasty, and many experts believe World Health Organization has avoided using the word "pandemic" since then.

Most experts believe that "pandemic" is considered to be infected people and places. If an infected person returns to his or her home country after being infected in the country where the outbreak occurred, this situation and the cases of infection from him or her are not counted in the "pandemic" statistics.

H1N1 spread largely because of the high frequency of global passenger traffic, which is different from the so-called "pandemic" definition of multiple regions with "independent community infection. ". As a result, public health experts are constantly revising their case-based calculations of "pandemics. ".

For COVID-19, public health experts focus on the analysis of "regional" infections, which are spread among people who have not been to China or Asia. The above mentioned University of Nebraska Expert Lawlor pointed out that in the United States, for example, many individual cases of human to human transmission in the United States are no longer imported infections, the epidemic in the United States has been spread within the country, "We have seen other developed countries with advanced biological control systems fail to fully control the spread of the epidemic, " added Lawlor, who estimated that 30-40 per cent of the US population could be infected.

By that measure, some experts believe the outbreak has reached the "pandemic" level, as six continents have become independent and endemic. However, Anthony Fauci, the National Director of Allergy and Institute of Medical Science and one of the US government's officials in charge of the outbreak, was slightly reticent about the pandemic, saying it was a matter of time, but not yet a full pandemic. The US Department of Defense predicted in early March that a global pandemic would come within 30 days.

If a COVID-19 is identified as a "pandemic" and a seasonal flu as a "pandemic" is a different concept, then society as a whole should be very cautious, FAUCI said. He explained that because scientists know the incidence, mortality and transmission of seasonal influenza viruses well and can predict them with relative accuracy, there are still very many unknown parameters for the new coronavirus, from lethality, incubation period, infectivity to asymptomatic infection, detection criteria and so on.

Amesh Adalja, an infectious disease specialist at Johns Hopkins University, told Caijing, "This [ has ] been a 'pandemic' , with or without an official announcement. There are no signs of control, mainly from the type of virus and the way it is spreading, " he said, more importantly, the next step should be to consider reallocating resources from quarantines, travel restrictions and airport surveillance to better hospital preparedness.

Cause panic or contempt

One of the main reasons who is wary of the word "pandemic" is the cautious approach of director-general Tan Desai.

"The imprudent use of the word 'pandemic' [ for an epidemic ] does not actually help, but runs the risk of creating unnecessary fear and ultimately paralyzing the system, " he said. "If [ the use of the word ] is likely to send a signal that we can not control the virus, which is not the case... we would never hesitate to use the word 'pandemic' if it accurately reflected the situation. "

His own standard for a pandemic is that the virus has a significant impact on at least two continents. In light of the current outbreak, he believes that the current use of the word is not consistent with the facts, but will cause panic. "This is not the time to focus on word play, " he stressed. "This is not going to help prevent new infections today or save a life. "

Lawrence Gostin, a professor at the Georgetown University and Director of the WHO's national and Global Center for Health Law Integration, notes that the word panic is literally contained in the word pandemic, needs to take into account the mood of the crowd. He further pointed out that the possibility of a "pandemic" of the new coronavirus was of course a concern, as it had a higher fatality rate than influenza, "But we hope to delay the announcement as long as possible until we have the vaccine, which is probably another 12-18 months. "

While World Health Organization is wary of using the word "pandemic" for fear of provoking panic, critics say the current cautious wording could lead some countries to downplay the epidemic. Recently, the outbreak began in the European continent and the United States, in the view of some medical experts, this is related to the countries concerned did not take timely and effective epidemic prevention measures.

Speaking at a news conference on March 5, Tan said some countries had not made all the effort and political commitment to fight the epidemic and that "the effort is not commensurate with the threat we face. "

He further stressed on social media that world leaders should fully implement the anti-epidemic plan and integrate every sector of government, not just the health sector, security, diplomacy, finance, commerce, transportation, trade, information, etc. should all be invested. "This is not a drill, this is not a time to give up, this is not a time to make excuses, this is a time to take all actions, " Tan stressed.
